# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jubilee-hospital-huntly
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] It takes its name from the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which had substantially different boundaries.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The Aberdeenshire Council area includes all of the areas of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire except the area making up Aberdeen City Council area, as well as part of Banffshire.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The historic county boundaries are still officially used for a few purposes, namely land registration and lieutenancy.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire Council is headquartered at Woodhill House in Aberdeen, making it the only Scottish council whose headquarters are located outside its jurisdiction.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeen itself forms a different council area (Aberdeen City).
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire borders onto Angus and Perth and Kinross to the south, Highland and Moray to the west and Aberdeen City to the east.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Traditionally, it has depended economically on the primary sector (agriculture, fishing, and forestry) and related processing industries.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Over the last 40 years, the development of the oil and gas industry and associated service sector has broadened Aberdeenshire's economic base, and contributed to a rapid population growth of some 50% since 1975.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Its land represents 8% of Scotland's overall territory.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] It covers an area of 6,313 square kilometres (2,437 sq mi).
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a rich prehistoric and historical heritage.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] It is the locus of a large number of Neolithic and Bronze Age archaeological sites, including Longman Hill, Kempstone Hill, Catto Long Barrow and Cairn Lee.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The area was settled in the Bronze Age by the Beaker culture, who arrived from the south around 2000–1800 BC.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Stone circles and cairns were constructed predominantly in this era.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Around the 1st century AD, the Taexali people, who left little history, were believed to have resided along the coast.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The Picts were the next documented inhabitants of the area and were no later than 800–900 AD.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The Romans also were in the area during this period, as they left signs at Kintore.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Christianity influenced the inhabitants early on, and there were Celtic monasteries at Old Deer and Monymusk.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Since medieval times, there have been many traditional paths that crossed the Mounth (a spur of mountainous land that extends from the higher inland range to the North Sea slightly north of Stonehaven) through present-day Aberdeenshire from the Scottish Lowlands to the Highlands.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Some of the most well known and historically important trackways are the Causey Mounth and Elsick Mounth.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire played an important role in the fighting between the Scottish dynasties.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] During the Anglo-Norman penetration, other families arrive, such as House of Balliol, Clan Bruce, and Clan Cumming (Comyn).
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] During the Scottish Wars of Independence, the King of England Edward I travelled across the area twice with his invading army, in 1296 and 1303.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] In 1307, Robert the Bruce was victorious near Inverurie.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] These new families set the stage for the upcoming rivalries during the 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] This rivalry grew worse during and after the Protestant Reformation when religion was another reason for conflict between the clans.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The Gordon family adhered to Catholicism and the Forbeses to Protestantism.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire was the historic seat of the clan Dempster.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Three universities were founded in the area prior to the 17th century, King's College in Old Aberdeen (1494), Marischal College in Aberdeen (1593), and the University of Fraserburgh (1592).
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] During the 17th century, Aberdeenshire was the location of more fighting, centred on the Marquess of Montrose and the Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] This period also saw increased wealth due to the increase in trade with Germany, Poland, and the Low Countries.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] After the end of the Revolution of 1688, an extended peaceful period was interrupted only by fleeting events such as the Rising of 1715 and the Rising of 1745.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The latter resulted in the end of the ascendancy of Episcopalianism and the feudal power of landowners.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] An era began of increased agricultural and industrial progress.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The present council area is named after the historic county of Aberdeenshire, which has different boundaries and ceased to be used for local government purposes in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Local government functions were shared between the two levels.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The modern council area was created in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] It covers the combined area of the Banff and Buchan, Gordon, and Kincardine and Deeside districts that had been created in 1975.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The present Aberdeenshire Council area therefore consists of all of the historic counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire (except the area of those two counties making up Aberdeen City), as well as the north-east portions of Banffshire.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The population of the council area has risen over 50% since 1971 to approximately 265,080 in 2024, representing 4.7% of Scotland's total.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's population has increased by 9.1% since 2001, while Scotland's total population grew by 3.8%.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The census lists a relatively high proportion of under 16s and slightly fewer working-age people compared with the Scottish average.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is one of the most homogeneous/indigenous regions of the UK.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] In 2011, 82.2% of residents identified as 'White Scottish', followed by 12.3% who are 'White British', whilst ethnic minorities constitute only 0.9% of the population.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The largest ethnic minority group is Asian Scottish/British at 0.8%.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] In addition to the English language, 48.8% of residents reported being able to speak and understand the Scots language.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,382 residents aged three and over, 121,797 (47.5%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] This is the greatest proportion of Scots speakers of any Scottish council area.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 256,377 residents aged three and over, 3,579 (1.4%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is estimated at £3,496M (2011), representing 5.2% of the Scottish total.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy is closely linked to Aberdeen City's (GDP £7,906M), and in 2011, the region as a whole was calculated to contribute 16.8% of Scotland's GDP.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Between 2012 and 2014, the combined Aberdeenshire and Aberdeen City economic forecast GDP growth rate is 8.6%, the highest growth rate of any local council area in the UK and above the Scottish rate of 4.8%.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] A significant proportion of Aberdeenshire's working residents commute to Aberdeen City for work, varying from 11.5% from Fraserburgh to 65% from Westhill.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Average Gross Weekly Earnings (for full-time employees employed in workplaces in Aberdeenshire in 2011) are £572.60.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the Scottish average by £2.10 and a fall of 2.6% on the 2010 figure.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The average gross weekly pay of people resident in Aberdeenshire is much higher, at £741.90, as many people commute out of Aberdeenshire, principally into Aberdeen City.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Total employment (excluding farm data) in Aberdeenshire is estimated at 93,700 employees (Business Register and Employment Survey 2009).
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The majority of employees work within the service sector, predominantly in public administration, education and health.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Almost 19% of employment is within the public sector.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire's economy remains closely linked to Aberdeen City's and the North Sea oil industry, with many employees in oil-related jobs.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] The average monthly unemployment (claimant count) rate for Aberdeenshire in 2011 was 1.5%.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] This is lower than the average rate of Aberdeen City (2.3%), Scotland (4.2%) and the UK (3.8%).
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] In the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'No' by a percentage of 60.4%.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] In the 2016 European Union membership referendum, Aberdeenshire voted 'Remain' by the third lowest margin of 55.0%.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] First and second lowest margin for 'Remain' were Moray (50.1%) and Dumfries and Galloway (53.1%).
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] There are numerous rivers and burns in Aberdeenshire, including Cowie Water, Carron Water, Burn of Muchalls, River Dee, River Don, River Ury, River Ythan, Water of Feugh, Burn of Myrehouse, Laeca Burn and Luther Water.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Numerous bays and estuaries are found along the seacoast of Aberdeenshire, including Banff Bay, Ythan Estuary, Stonehaven Bay and Thornyhive Bay.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire has a marine west coast climate on the Köppen climate classification.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Aberdeenshire is in the rain shadow of the Grampians, therefore it has a generally dry climate for a maritime region, with portions of the coast receiving 25 inches (64 cm) of moisture annually.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Summers are mild, and winters are typically cold in Aberdeenshire; Coastal temperatures are moderated by the North Sea such that coastal areas are typically cooler in the summer and warmer in the winter than inland locations.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aberdeenshire] Coastal areas are also subject to haar, or coastal fog.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The **British Red Cross Society** (Welsh: *Y Groes Goch Brydeinig*) is the United Kingdom body of the worldwide neutral and impartial humanitarian network the International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The society was formed in 1870, and is a registered charity with 10,500 volunteers and 3,500 staff.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] At the heart of their work is providing help to people in crisis, both in the UK and overseas.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The Red Cross is committed to helping people without discrimination, regardless of their ethnic origin, nationality, political beliefs or religion.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Queen Elizabeth II was the patron of the society until her death in 2022, and was replaced by her successor King Charles III, who previously served as president between 2003 and 2024.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In the year ending December 2023, the charity's income was £331 million, which included £32M from government contracts and £34M from government grants.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Total expenditure was £323M, of which £246M (76%) of its income delivering its charitable activities.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The mission of the British Red Cross is to mobilise the power of humanity so that individuals and communities can prepare for, deal with and recover from a crisis, summed up by the strapline 'refusing to ignore people in crisis'.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross also has four values, which guide the way they work.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross was formed in 1870, just seven years after the formation of the international movement in Switzerland.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This followed the outbreak of the Franco-Prussian War (1870–1871), and a move across Europe to form similar societies.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The society was founded as the **British National Society for Aid to the Sick and Wounded in War** at a public meeting chaired by Robert Loyd-Lindsay in London on 4 August 1870.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] It assisted in providing aid to both warring armies in the Franco-Prussian War and subsequent 19th-century conflicts, under the protection of the Red Cross Emblem.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The society was one of several British volunteer medical organisations to serve in the war.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Queen Victoria was the organisation's first patron.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In 1905, 35 years after its formation, the society was reconstituted as the British Red Cross Society, and was granted its first royal charter in 1908 by King Edward VII, who became the patron.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] His consort, Queen Alexandra, became its president.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In the following years, King George V, King George VI and Queen Elizabeth II assumed the position of patron, while Queen Mary and Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother served as presidents.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] King Charles III, who was the society's president between 2003 and 2024, was named patron in May 2024.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Following the start of the Great War in 1914, the British Red Cross joined forces with the Order of St John Ambulance to form the Joint War committee and Joint War Organisation.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] They pooled resources and formed Voluntary Aid Detachments (or VADs) with members trained in First Aid, Nursing, Cookery, Hygiene and Sanitation.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] These detachments all worked under the protection of the Red Cross, working in hospitals, rest stations, work parties and supply centres.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The Joint War Organisation also aided assistance at the front line, supplying the first motorised ambulances to the battlefields, which were significantly more efficient than the horse-drawn ambulances they replaced.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] It was active in setting up centres for recording the wounded and missing.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Red Cross volunteers searched towns, villages and hospitals where fighting had occurred, noting names of the missing, the injured and the dead.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This formed the basis of the international Message and Tracing service, still running today.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Amongst the more innovative activities of the Red Cross in the war was the training of Airedale Terrier dogs to search for wounded soldiers on battlefields.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Christie's auction house in Britain held an auction each year from 1915 to 1918 to benefit the Red Cross.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] People all across the United Kingdom donated their jewelry to help raise money.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In 1918 one of the auctioned pieces was the Red Cross diamond.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross stayed involved with blood transfusion past the formation of the National Blood Service and it retained an ancillary role until 1987.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross was instrumental in starting overseas societies throughout the British Empire and Commonwealth, most of which are now independent national societies.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In 1924, the British Red Cross started its youth movement, helping to promote its values to a younger generation.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] After the declaration of war in 1939, the British Red Cross once again joined with St John to form the Joint War Organisation, again affording the St John volunteers protection under the Red Cross emblem.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The organisation once again worked in hospitals, care home, nurseries, ambulance units, rest stations and more, much of which was funded by the Duke of Gloucester's Red Cross and St John appeal, which had raised over £54 million by 1946.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The Red Cross also arranged parcels for prisoners of war, following the provisions of the third Geneva convention in 1929, which laid out strict rules for the treatment of PoWs.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The Joint War Organisation sent standard food parcels, invalid food parcels, medical supplies, educational books and recreational materials to prisoners of war worldwide.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] During the conflict, over 20 million standard food parcels were sent.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] During the German occupation of the Channel Islands, the islanders were helped to avoid starvation with food parcels brought by the Red Cross ship SS *Vega*.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The immediate priorities for the British Red Cross following the war, were the huge number of displaced civilians caused by forced migration during the war.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The Red Cross provided much relief for these people, including basic supplies, and helping to reunite people through the Messaging and Tracing Service.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This work led to the provisions in the 1949 Fourth Geneva Convention to protect civilians caught up in war.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Since then, the British Red Cross has provided relief to people worldwide, including during the Hungarian Revolution of 1956, in Vietnam in 1976, Famine in Africa in the 1980s and the 1999 Armenia, Colombia earthquake.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Whilst the society no longer sends its volunteers abroad, it is a leading contributor of delegates to the International Red Cross pool of emergency relief workers.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Between 1948 and 1967, the British Red Cross and the St Andrew's Ambulance Association jointly operated the Scottish Ambulance Service, under contract to the National Health Service.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] NHS Scotland took over full responsibility for the service in 1974.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In the UK, the society has been active at many major disasters, from the coal tip slide at Aberfan in 1966, the Pan Am Flight 103 bombing at Lockerbie in 1988, to the 7 July 2005 London bombings.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] They provide support on all levels, from front line medical provision, to running helplines for worried relatives and long term emotional care for the victims.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In July 2008, the Prince of Wales and the Duchess of Cornwall hosted a garden party at Buckingham Palace to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the granting of the society's royal charter.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross is recognised by the UK Government as one of three Voluntary Aid Societies, the other two being St John Ambulance and St.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] It is the sole Red Cross Society for the United Kingdom and the British Overseas Territories.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross provides a wide range of services to assist the emergency services and statutory authorities, ranging from first aid support and distribution of aid during a crisis to managing a disaster appeal scheme and providing telephone support lines in its aftermath.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Notably, all services of the British Red Cross can be utilised for the emergency response service, as the situation demands.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] For example, the therapeutic care service can provide support at a rest centre for survivors, while Ambulances can assist the NHS in caring for the injured.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The emergency response service has been present at most types of major emergency such as the London bombings, Manchester Arena bombing, Grenfell Tower fire, rail crashes, other fires, and floods.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross operate this service throughout its territory, available 24 hours a day but, contrary to popular belief, does not send its volunteers abroad, as overseas disasters will be dealt with by the society in the country affected.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement is the largest provider of first aid in the world.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross was possibly most recognised in the UK for its work as a leading provider of first aid at public events across the UK.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This stopped in 2020, by the British Red Cross, when it announced in 2019 that it would stop all Event First Aid.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Thousands of volunteers gave care to the injured at events of all sizes including Premiership football games, concerts and large-scale running events such as the Great North Run.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The training undertaken by Event First Aid Service volunteers varied, and advanced training was available to those volunteers who wished to undertake it, which included rising to the level of Ambulance Crew, or even undertaking training to become a qualified Ambulance technician.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The closure of event first aiders also saw the end of the Voluntary Medical Service Medal being issued to British Red Cross volunteers, much to their dismay, however it is still issued to St Andrew's first aid volunteers.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Ambulance crews undergo national standard training and examination and are then qualified to offer an advanced level of care to sick and injured patients.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] British Red Cross provide ambulance support for the North East Ambulance Service.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The BRC also provide PTS in South East Wales, with paid Ambulance Care Assistants being trained and deployed in house.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Specialist units existed within the first aid provision including the Cycle Response Unit, which allowed trained cyclists with enhanced first aid skills to access areas inaccessible to full ambulance vehicles.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This was initially sponsored by Land Rover.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In October 2019, the British Red Cross announced to volunteers that it would cease providing Event First Aid services on 31 March 2020.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Its Ambulance Support services continue.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross is a provider of first aid training in the United Kingdom.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] It trains people both on a community and a commercial basis.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The commercial training teams run nationally recognised First aid courses specifically designed to provide skills for use at work.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross have been running these courses for over 25 years and over 120,000 people are trained each year .
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Courses range from a basic Emergency Life Support to a three-day First Aid at Work (FAW) course recognised by the Health and Safety Executive.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] On a community basis, the British Red Cross is also well known as providing many first aid courses across the country to members of the public, as well as reaching out to schools, community groups and minority groups.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] One of the projects of the British Red Cross is Everyday First Aid, which seeks to provide training to those who would not otherwise get the opportunity to undertake such training, such as people with disabilities.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] First aid training programmes delivered by the Red Cross are renowned for giving participants both the skills and confidence to use what they have learnt, with a combination of theoretical knowledge and practical sessions.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Formerly known as Fire Victim Support, this service is one of the more recent to be started by the British Red Cross.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Covering most, but not yet all, of the UK, the British Red Cross provide assistance at the request of the local fire and rescue service to those in the immediate aftermath of emergencies such as a house fire or road traffic accident.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Typically a team of two volunteers with a customised vehicle will respond to victims and provide them with shelter, food, first aid, clothing, toiletries, washing facilities and moral support.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Volunteers will assist with the process of dealing with local authority housing departments or insurance companies to enable rehousing.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The Red Cross also are able to set up a number of help lines in connection with major incidents.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] British Red Cross provides the public alongside some NHS hospital trusts to borrow a wheelchair for free.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This operates throughout United Kingdom, including Northern Ireland.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] They nearly have 1,000 different offices that operate this service.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This service is operated by the British Red Cross Health and Social Department.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This service provides a way of learning about and understanding the world – best thought of as a form of citizenship education.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] It is not religious or political, but is centrally concerned with our shared humanity.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] At the core of humanitarian action and thinking is a desire to contribute to saving lives and reducing suffering.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Humanitarian education invites exploration of those actions and thoughts.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Humanitarian Education helps students examine what motivates people, including themselves, and extends to other societies, times, and cultures.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] It explores the wider issues, sometimes surprisingly complex, that arise when people help each other.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross provides educational resources for teachers and trained peer education volunteers.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In September 2008 the British Red Cross launched an alternate reality game called Traces of Hope to help educate people about the work the Red Cross does in conflict areas and the effect war has on civilians.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross, in some areas, provides short-term care and support for people recently returned from hospital, or recently having suffered an injury that otherwise would result in a hospital or care facility admission.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] There is small Red Cross team working in the discharge lounge in A&E at Leighton Hospital who use their own cars to drive vulnerable patients home and settle them in.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The following day they make a follow-up – a phone call.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] If not, they can refer on to the BRC's Home from Hospital scheme that provides up to six weeks social support such as help with shopping and befriending.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] There are 86 Home from Hospital services.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] While referrals for this service can come from health and social care professionals, people can also self-refer.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Referrals for this service usually come from healthcare professionals, but people can self-refer, as the service can also be provided at community meeting places and homes.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The crisis intervention community support service which operates in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire and Cheshire provides crisis emotional support and assists people in maintaining their independent living skills during a period of crisis.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] It helps to prevent admission to hospital or respite care by providing short, targeted interventions.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The team in Nottingham team consists of 12 healthcare assistants.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] During 2014, it claimed that 748 admissions were avoided, which would have cost about £1.5 million.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The service costs the two local Clinical Commissioning Groups just under £250,000 a year to run.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross provides a number of transport schemes to get people with limited access to transport, either with their own car or public transport, from place to place.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Services can be provided by car or minibus, with an escort if appropriate, in order to help people lead a normal life, such as journeys for medical appointments and to shops.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This includes in some areas 'Dial-a-Ride' schemes, where elderly or disabled people can phone and are transported by specially adapted minibus door to door.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In addition, the British Red Cross also provides, in some areas, ambulance transport, either seated or stretcher, between places of treatment, or for admissions and discharges of patients at hospital.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This is operated by the trained ambulance crews also used for emergency ambulance provision (see above).
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Since 1989, the British Red Cross has provided a range of services to refugees, including managing a number of refugee reception centres nationwide.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The work includes providing refugee orientation services and ensuring that life essentials, such as shelter and food are provided for.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In cases of destitution, the British Red Cross can provide short-term emergency help, and advice on accessing other services.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] A peer befriending service also exists to provide help to vulnerable refugees, such as young people and women.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross can also assist in cases of large-scale arrivals to the United Kingdom.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Since September 2008, the British Red Cross has been a member of the European Council on Refugees and Exiles (ECRE).
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This is another specialised international service, operated by the majority of national Red Cross and Red Crescent societies worldwide.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Started to help the refugees of war, this service now extends to any person, who has lost touch with family through war or disaster.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The global Red Cross and Red Crescent network uses local volunteers to find relations, put them back in touch, or simply pass messages.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross also provides this service to those separated by the Second World War.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This aspect hit the headlines when a volunteer famous for doing this work for 20 years was dismissed.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Since the International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement is worldwide, there are volunteers in the nation affected that can provide help in disaster situations.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] However, the British Red Cross, in common with other national societies, sends paid personnel abroad, called *delegates*, who have specialised skills such as in logistics, to assist the agencies in the aftermath of a major international disaster.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This is in addition to resources the British Red Cross can provide, in co-operation with the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross also provides assistance in recovery after the immediate post-disaster situation, helping prepare communities for future emergencies and facilitating long-term development.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Muriel Skeet, a British nurse, was the Nursing Advisor and Chief Nursing Officer (CNO) to the British Red Cross Society from 1970 until 1978.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] During this time she published her manual for relief work in 1977.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross works closely with other Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies to improve the health and care situation of vulnerable communities abroad.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross has been supporting HIV work internationally since the mid-1980s, for example in China, South Africa and Ethiopia.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The charity helps combat Tuberculosis in Turkmenistan, Kyrgyzstan and Russia, including supporting programmes involved in raising awareness and supporting those affected in their homes.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Furthermore, it supports water and sanitation activities in Zambia, Zimbabwe, Mozambique, Uganda, Ethiopia, Rwanda and Cambodia, by providing safer drinking water and sanitation facilities and educating populations.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross also supports programmes assisting healthcare in conflict areas, such as Iraq and Sudan.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross supports the Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement's mission to fight the spread of HIV and AIDS worldwide.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The society works with groups of young people to fight discrimination and stigma as well as reducing complacency about catching the disease.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] On World AIDS Day (1 December) 2007, the society launched an on-line campaign called "HIV: What's the story?" to target young people in the UK and overseas.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The campaign also makes extensive use of social networking sites such as Facebook and Bebo.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] British Red Cross won the Queen Elizabeth II Platinum Jubilee Award for Volunteering for their work to empower young people.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] As a charity, the British Red Cross relies heavily on voluntary contributions from members of the public and organisations, in order to carry out its work.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] In addition, it does also make money from its commercial services, including First Aid Training (for the workplace), First aid provision at events and providing auxiliary crews to the ambulance services.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Whilst personal donations are important, the scale of corporate donations can make a huge difference to the society, and initiatives such as being the Tesco charity of the year in 2007 make large contributions to central funds.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Every year, many events are held, including sponsored bike rides, walks and even skydives.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Red Cross Appeal Week (formerly known as Red Cross Flag Week), is held annually in May, to coincide with the birthday of Red Cross founder, Henry Dunant.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This is a week where staff and volunteers are asked to donate two hours to run street and private premises collections.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross helps to fund, and is aided with funds raised by, the national will-making scheme Will Aid, in which participating solicitors waive their usual fee to write a basic will and in exchange invite the client to donate to charity.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] To help boost support for the cause, the Red Cross has a number of celebrity ambassadors which include Angela Rippon, Michael Buerk, James McAvoy, David Bull, Josie d'Arby, Nancy Dell'Olio, Konnie Huq, Craig Gannon and Dougray Scott.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross runs a museum containing a variety of materials from its beginnings in 1870 to the present day.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] This museum is a member of The London Museums of Health & Medicine group.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The collections include posters, photographs, badges worn by Society members, medals awarded to Society members, medical equipment and fundraising materials.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The museum is free to enter and can be visited without booking.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] Guided tours of the museum and research visits to the archives must be booked in advance.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The British Red Cross sent a warning letter to the developers of the indie game *Prison Architect* in 2016.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The organisation claims that, by using red cross images on *Prison Architect* ambulances and paramedics, the game has violated the Geneva Conventions.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The Red Cross symbol (along with the Red Crescent and the Red Crystal) is protected under the Geneva Convention, this is to distinguish armed combatants from impartial humanitarian aid workers.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The warning letter was sent due to the possibility of the red cross being mistaken as a sign of first aid, and not as protected humanitarian work.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The Red Cross fear that the mistaken use may cause the symbol's meaning to be misinterpreted during war.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/british-red-cross] The *Prison Architect* developers changed the cross to green, a colour commonly on medical signs and equipment (as shown by various ISO Standards) so its use is more commonly associated with medical help.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/chalmers-hospital-banff] Chalmers Hospital was founded by Alexander Chalmers (died 11 August 1835), a merchant of Banff, who left the whole of his estate to be applied, upon the death of his wife, towards funding and building a hospital for the people in the Royal Burgh of Banff.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/chalmers-hospital-banff] Mrs Chalmers died in 1861, and Chalmers Hospital opened on 19 July 1864.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/chalmers-hospital-banff] The original 'deed of mortification' set out that this was for any destitute sick persons born, domiciled or resident in the Banff area, although in 1929 the trustees successfully petitioned for the removal of this restriction.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/chalmers-hospital-banff] Some major redevelopment work began in October 2008, after the hospital attracted criticism for not being up to date, with some of the interior features having been there since the Second World War.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital remained open during the work, although the Findlater ward services were moved to Campbell Hospital in Portsoy until the Findlater ward was refurbished, and Seafield and Deveron ward were merged.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/chalmers-hospital-banff] The midwifery unit was demolished and rebuilt to provide modern facilities.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/chalmers-hospital-banff] Numerous other internal changes were also made inside, including X-ray facilities being moved to a different area of the building.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/chalmers-hospital-banff] The redevelopment also provided upgraded facilities for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy and podiatry.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/chalmers-hospital-banff] The completion of the redevelopment was recognised with a visit by the Princess Royal in March 2012.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital is supported by GPs from Banff, Gamrie, Deveron, Macduff, Portsoy and Aberchirder Medical Practices.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/jubilee-hospital-huntly] The **Jubilee Hospital** is a community hospital in Huntly, Aberdeenshire, Scotland.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/jubilee-hospital-huntly] The hospital, which was financed by public subscription to honour the Golden Jubilee of Queen Victoria, was designed by Robert Duncan and opened in November 1889.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/jubilee-hospital-huntly] It served as a Red Cross hospital during the First World War.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/jubilee-hospital-huntly] An isolation unit for treating people with tuberculosis was added in 1925 and a day case unit was added in 1938.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/jubilee-hospital-huntly] After tuberculosis had been largely eradicated, the isolation unit was converted into a maternity unit in 1944.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/jubilee-hospital-huntly] In August 2014 the hospital was used as a safe refuge for residents of local care homes in the wake of Hurricane Bertha.
[src:jubilee-hospital-huntly/jubilee-hospital-huntly] The hospital has a small x-ray department with a full-time radiographer who also provides an electrocardiography and pregnancy ultrasound scanning service.
